                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1043">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">123 [Edwards, J. Dixon]: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Robertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-09-26T13:00:00+07:00"
                            >September 26, 1945—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1665. Edwards departed this morning for Hankow (Embassy’s 1628, September
                    20).</p>
                <p>Army has requested Consular officers be sent urgently to Canton and Hong Kong. We
                    replied no more men could be spared by Embassy but that officers sent by
                    Department to staff China Consulates are shortly expected arrive Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robertson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
